export const AI_CONTEXT = "You are an expert on Salesforce Salesforce Nonprofit Cloud (NONPROFITCLOUD) Spring '26.\nAnswer questions based ONLY on the following product knowledge. If the question is not about NONPROFITCLOUD or you are unsure, say so clearly. Keep answers concise (2-4 sentences).\nWhen mentioning domains or components, include markdown links using the URLs from the Links section below.\n\n## Domains (20)\n- **Constituents** (constituents): The foundation of Nonprofit Cloud's data model.\n- **Households & Groups** (households): Models households and other group affiliations using Party Relationship Groups.\n- **Relationships** (relationships): Tracks the connections between constituents at every level: individual-to-individual, individual-to-organization, and organization-to-organization.\n- **Contact Information** (contact_points): Manages addresses, email addresses, and phone numbers using Salesforce's polymorphic Contact Point objects.\n- **Fundraising Pipeline** (fundraising): Manages the cultivation and solicitation pipeline for major gifts, grants, and significant donor relationships.\n- **Gift Commitments** (gift_commitments): Manages pledges, recurring donations, and multi-payment gift agreements.\n- **Gift Transactions** (gift_transactions): Tracks every received gift and payment as a discrete transaction record.\n- **Gift Entry & Processing** (gift_entry): Provides efficient interfaces for recording and processing donations.\n- **Gift Designations** (designations): Controls how donation amounts are allocated to specific funds and purposes.\n- **Soft Credits** (soft_credits): Provides a unified attribution model for recognizing constituents who influenced or facilitated a gift without being the primary donor.\n- **Campaigns & Outreach** (campaigns): Manages fundraising campaigns and tracks donor outreach across channels.\n- **Program Management** (programs): Tracks the services and programs your nonprofit delivers to constituents.\n- **Case Management** (case_management): Equips case managers and social workers with tools for intake, assessment, and personalized care planning.\n- **Outcome Management** (outcomes): Defines, measures, and evaluates the impact of your programs using a structured theory of change framework.\n- **Volunteer Management** (volunteers): Streamlines the end-to-end volunteer lifecycle from recruitment to hour tracking and reporting.\n- **Grantmaking** (grantmaking): Streamlines the grant management process for organizations that fund other nonprofits or community projects.\n- **Agentforce & Einstein AI** (agentforce): Brings generative AI and conversational AI capabilities to Nonprofit Cloud.\n- **Action Plans** (action_plans): Automates multi-step task sequences using template-driven action plans.\n- **Security & Access** (security): Manages licensing, permissions, and data access controls for Nonprofit Cloud.\n- **Setup & Configuration** (setup): Central hub for configuring all Nonprofit Cloud features.\n\n## Key Components (78)\n- **Person Accounts** [Constituents]: Represents individual constituents such as donors, volunteers, and program participants. Person Accounts are the recommended way to represent individuals in Nonprofit Cloud. They combine the Account and Contact objects into a single record, giving each person a unified view that shows their donations, relationships, program enrollments, and volunteer activities in one place. Person Accounts are strongly recommended for customers using Fundraising or Program Management, though Grantmaking-only organizations that primarily make grants to organizations may prefer the standard Contact plus Business Account model instead.\n- **Business Accounts** [Constituents]: Represents organizations such as foundations, corporate donors, matching gift employers, and partner agencies. Business Accounts in Nonprofit Cloud represent every type of organization your nonprofit works with, including foundations, corporate sponsors, matching gift employers, government agencies, and partner organizations. They use the standard Salesforce Account object with the Business Account record type, providing a familiar data model that integrates with all platform features including reports, dashboards, and automation.\n- **Contact Profiles** [Constituents]: Extends constituent records with fundraising-specific attributes. The Contact Profile object stores fundraising-specific attributes that go beyond what standard Account and Contact fields provide. Key fields include the Recurring Donor Type, which indicates whether the constituent is a sustaining, lapsed, or prospective recurring donor, and the Donor Classification, which supports segmentation categories like Major Donor, Mid-Level, or Annual Fund. These fields drive personalized donor engagement workflows.\n- **Account Hierarchies** [Constituents]: Models parent-child relationships between organizations for multi-office or affiliated structures. Account hierarchies let you model the parent-child relationships between organizations so you can see the complete picture of corporate families, foundation networks, and multi-office nonprofits. The Parent Account lookup on the Account object links subsidiaries to their headquarters, and Salesforce reports can aggregate data across the entire hierarchy for comprehensive institutional reporting.\n- **Party Relationship Groups** [Households & Groups]: The container object for modeling households and other group types. Party Relationship Groups are the core of Nonprofit Cloud's household model. Each group is backed by a Business Account and has a Type field that classifies it as a Household, Affinity Group, Board, or any custom type your organization defines. Members are connected through Account Contact Relationships, which track each person's role, active status, and date range within the group.\n- **Household Membership** [Households & Groups]: Account Contact Relationships link individuals to their household group with specific roles. Account Contact Relationships serve as the membership link between individuals and their household groups. Each record connects a Person Account (the individual) to a Business Account (the household or organization) with one or more roles, an active status flag, and start and end dates. Roles such as Head of Household, Spouse, Dependent, and Member capture the person's position within the group.\n- **Household Addressing** [Households & Groups]: Manages shared contact information for household members. Household addressing in Nonprofit Cloud coordinates mailing preferences across household members. When multiple Person Accounts share a household through a Party Relationship Group, their Contact Point Address records can reference the shared household address. The primary address designation on each contact point determines which address is used for mailings and communications.\n- **Contact Contact Relationships** [Relationships]: Models direct relationships between individuals. Contact Contact Relationships track person-to-person connections that are essential for understanding donor networks and family structures. Each record links two contacts with reciprocal roles defined by a Party Role Relationship, such as Spouse/Spouse, Parent/Child, or Mentor/Mentee. The relationship appears on both individuals' record pages, giving staff a complete view of each person's network.\n- **Account Contact Relationships** [Relationships]: Links individuals to organizations with specific roles. Account Contact Relationships are the most versatile relationship type in Nonprofit Cloud, connecting individuals to organizations with specific roles and date ranges. They serve double duty as both household membership records (linking Person Accounts to Party Relationship Group Business Accounts) and organizational affiliation records (linking individuals to employers, boards, and partner agencies).\n- **Account Account Relationships** [Relationships]: Models relationships between organizations, such as corporate affiliations, foundation-grantee relationships, partner agency connections, and vendor relationships. Account Account Relationships map the connections between organizations in your ecosystem. Each record links two Business Accounts with a relationship type and directional roles, capturing connections such as corporate parent/subsidiary, foundation/grantee, partner agency, and vendor relationships. These records help institutional fundraisers and grantmakers understand the organizational landscape around their prospects.\n- **Party Role Relationships** [Relationships]: Metadata that defines the available relationship types and their reciprocal labels. Party Role Relationships are the configuration records that define what types of relationships staff can create. Each record specifies a forward label (such as Parent), a reciprocal label (such as Child), a relationship type category (Family, Professional, Community), and whether it applies to individual-to-individual or organization-to-organization connections. Admins create and manage these records to control the picklist of available relationship types.\n- **Contact Point Addresses** [Contact Information]: Stores physical mailing and location addresses for constituents. Contact Point Addresses replace NPSP's custom Address object with a standardized Salesforce platform object for managing physical addresses. Each record stores a complete address with street, city, state, postal code, and country fields, along with an address type classification and a primary designation flag. Constituents can have multiple addresses for different purposes, and the IsPrimary flag determines which address is used for mailings.\n- **Contact Point Emails** [Contact Information]: Stores email addresses for constituents with support for multiple records per person. Contact Point Email records store email addresses for constituents using the standard Salesforce platform object. Each record captures the email address itself, a type classification such as Personal, Work, or Other, and a primary designation. Multiple email records per constituent enable tracking of personal and professional email addresses while clearly identifying the preferred address for communications.\n- **Contact Point Phones** [Contact Information]: Stores phone numbers for constituents with support for multiple records per person. Contact Point Phone records provide a standardized way to store multiple phone numbers per constituent. Each record captures the telephone number, a type classification (Home, Mobile, Work, Fax), and a primary designation flag. This model supports the common need to track both personal and professional phone numbers for donors and volunteers.\n- **Opportunities** [Fundraising Pipeline]: Tracks major gift solicitations, grant proposals, and significant fundraising asks. Opportunities in Nonprofit Cloud represent the cultivation and solicitation phase of fundraising before gifts are formalized into commitments or transactions. Each opportunity moves through configurable pipeline stages with probability percentages, expected amounts, and close dates. Record types on the Opportunity object enable different sales processes for major gifts, grants, planned giving, and other fundraising types, each with its own stage sequence.\n- **Opportunity Contact Roles** [Fundraising Pipeline]: Associates multiple constituents with an opportunity and defines each person's role in the solicitation. Opportunity Contact Roles link multiple individuals to a fundraising opportunity and define each person's involvement in the solicitation process. Standard roles include Primary Donor, Influencer, Decision Maker, and Soft Credit Recipient, and organizations can add custom roles to match their cultivation workflow. The IsPrimary flag identifies the main contact for the opportunity.\n- **Sales Processes** [Fundraising Pipeline]: Defines the stage sequences that opportunities follow from identification to close. Sales Processes in Nonprofit Cloud define the stage sequences that fundraising opportunities follow from identification to close. Different record types on the Opportunity object map to different processes, so major gifts can follow stages like Identification, Cultivation, Solicitation, Negotiation, and Stewardship, while inbound grants follow Prospecting, Proposal, Review, and Award stages. Admins can configure additional processes for planned giving, corporate sponsorships, and other fundraising types.\n- **Fundraising Analytics** [Fundraising Pipeline]: Provides high-level visibility into fundraising performance through dashboards and reports. The Fundraising Strategy app provides a top-level understanding of fundraising activities and data. Executives and top-level managers use it to check on their organization's fundraising progress and plan future fundraising efforts. It includes dashboards that aggregate pipeline health, total giving, campaign performance, and donor retention metrics into actionable views.\n- **Commitment Records** [Gift Commitments]: The core object tracking a donor's commitment to give. Gift Commitments track all types of donor promises to give, including one-time pledges, multi-payment gifts, and open-ended recurring donations. Each commitment record captures the schedule type (Recurring for regular installments or Custom for non-recurring multi-payment gifts), the donor account, campaign attribution, and an originating opportunity if the gift was solicited. The commitment status automatically progresses through Draft, Active, Paused, Lapsed, Failing, and Closed based on transaction patterns.\n- **Commitment Schedules** [Gift Commitments]: Defines the installment pattern for a commitment: frequency (monthly, quarterly, annually), interval, day of month, effective start and end dates, and amount per installment. Gift Commitment Schedules define when and how much a donor pays against their commitment. For recurring commitments, the schedule specifies the transaction period (monthly, quarterly, annually), the day of the month installments are due, the interval between payments, the payment start and end dates, and the installment amount. The system uses this information to automatically generate gift transaction records for each upcoming installment.\n- **Commitment Lifecycle** [Gift Commitments]: Manages the full lifecycle of recurring and pledged gifts. The commitment lifecycle encompasses all the ways a donor's ongoing giving relationship can change over time. Fundraising provides dedicated flows for each lifecycle operation: Upgrade/Downgrade changes the gift amount, Pause temporarily suspends installments for a specified period, Resume restarts a paused schedule, Update Payment Method switches the payment instrument, and Close ends the commitment entirely.\n- **Change Attribution Log** [Gift Commitments]: Records every modification to a gift commitment for audit and attribution purposes. The Gift Commitment Change Attribution Log automatically records every modification made to a gift commitment, creating a complete audit trail. Each log entry captures the change type (upgrade, downgrade, pause, resume, payment method change), the per-day amount impact of the change, and the campaign or outreach source code that influenced the donor's decision to modify their giving.\n- **Transaction Records** [Gift Transactions]: The core object for tracking received gifts. Gift Transactions are the record of truth for every donation received by your organization. Each transaction captures the original amount, current amount (which changes after refunds), payment method, gift vehicle type, gift received date, and the donor's account. Transactions are attributed to campaigns and outreach source codes for granular tracking of which fundraising efforts generate revenue.\n- **Payment Instruments** [Gift Transactions]: Stores donor payment method information such as credit card last four digits, expiration dates, and ACH details. Payment Instruments store secure references to donor payment methods used for recurring commitments. Each record captures the payment type (Credit Card, ACH, Bank Transfer), last four digits of the card or account number, expiration date, and an active status flag. These records are linked to Gift Commitment Schedules to track which payment method is used for each installment.\n- **Refund Processing** [Gift Transactions]: Creates refund records for full or partial gift returns. Refund processing in Nonprofit Cloud creates Gift Refund records linked to the original transaction to maintain a complete financial history. Staff can create full or partial refunds from the Gift Refunds related list on any paid transaction. Each refund record captures the refund amount, refund date, and refund status, and when the status is set to Completed, the system automatically updates the refund amount and current amount fields on the related transaction.\n- **Acknowledgments** [Gift Transactions]: Tracks the acknowledgment status and date for gift transactions. Gift acknowledgment tracking uses the Acknowledgment Status field on gift transactions to manage the lifecycle of donor thank-you communications. Statuses include Not Sent, Sent, and Failed, giving fundraising operations staff visibility into which donors still need to be acknowledged. Batch acknowledgment generation is available from the Fundraising Operations Home page for processing large volumes of thank-yous efficiently.\n- **Gift Entry Window** [Gift Entry & Processing]: A single-form interface for creating individual gifts. The Gift Entry Window provides a streamlined single-form workflow for recording individual donations. Staff can enter a standalone one-time gift, create a new gift commitment along with its first transaction, or match a payment to an existing commitment's installment schedule. The form captures the donor, amount, payment method, gift designations, and soft credits all in one place, reducing the number of clicks needed to process a donation.\n- **Gift Entry Grid** [Gift Entry & Processing]: A tabular data entry interface for rapidly creating multiple gifts. The Gift Entry Grid provides a spreadsheet-like interface for rapidly entering multiple gifts in a tabular format, supporting up to 200 rows per session. Admins customize the grid through Gift Entry Grid templates that control which columns appear, their order, width, whether they are required or hidden, and their default values. Templates can be cloned from the Salesforce Gift Entry Standard Template and customized for different entry scenarios.\n- **Gift Batches** [Gift Entry & Processing]: Groups gift entries for bulk processing. Gift Batches group multiple gift entries for organized bulk processing. Each batch has an associated Gift Entry Grid template, an expected gift count, and an estimated value for reconciliation against the actual entries. This enables fundraising operations teams to process large volumes of donations systematically while catching discrepancies before committing.\n- **CSV Data Import** [Gift Entry & Processing]: Enables importing large volumes of donation data from external systems using CSV Data Management for Industries. CSV Data Management enables importing large volumes of donation data from external systems into Nonprofit Cloud. Import files are prepared with columns mapped to Gift Entry fields, and each file is associated with a Gift Batch that provides the processing container. This approach supports annual fund drives, event registrations, migration scenarios from other systems, and regular imports from external donation platforms.\n- **Gift Designations** [Gift Designations]: Named funding purposes that donors can direct their gifts toward. A Gift Designation is a fund that represents a specific purpose for a gift, such as an earthquake relocation fund, a scholarship fund, or a fund for after-school care. Organizations create designations for each fund they want to track and can set one designation as the org-wide default for all unrestricted gift amounts. The default designation ensures that every dollar is tracked even when donors do not specify a purpose for their gift.\n- **Transaction Designations** [Gift Designations]: Junction objects that link gift transactions to gift designations with a percentage or amount allocation. Gift Transaction Designations are the junction records that link each gift transaction to one or more gift designations with a specific percentage or dollar amount allocation. Each transaction can have up to 50 designations, enabling complex split gifts where a donor directs their contribution across multiple funds. The sum of all designation percentages must be equal to or less than 100%.\n- **Default Designations** [Gift Designations]: Manages the inheritance hierarchy that automatically assigns designations to gifts. Gift Default Designations manage the automatic inheritance hierarchy that determines how gifts are allocated to funds when no explicit designation is specified. The hierarchy for gift commitments checks the opportunity first, then the campaign, and finally the org-wide default. For gift transactions created during gift entry, the hierarchy checks the campaign, commitment, opportunity, and org-wide default in order of availability.\n- **Designation Reporting** [Gift Designations]: Provides rollup reporting and impact analysis by designation. Designation reporting relies on Data Processing Engine to calculate rollup fields on Gift Designation records from the underlying Gift Transaction Designation data. The GiftDesignation DPE definition aggregates total amounts, transaction counts, and other metrics across all allocations to each designation, giving fund managers real-time visibility into fundraising progress for each purpose.\n- **Gift Soft Credits** [Soft Credits]: Records attribution for constituents who influenced a donation. Gift Soft Credits provide a unified way to recognize constituents who influenced or facilitated a donation without being the primary donor. Each soft credit record links to a gift transaction and a credited account with a role such as Influence, Tribute, Solicitation, Household Member, or Matched Donor. Partial amounts or percentages can be assigned when multiple people contributed to securing a gift, and the soft credit amount can be up to 100% of the gift.\n- **Matching Gift Tracking** [Soft Credits]: Tracks employer matching programs where organizations match employee donations. Matching gift tracking in Nonprofit Cloud uses the Matching Employer Transaction lookup field on the Gift Transaction object to connect an employee's original donation with the corporate matching gift. When a matching gift is received, staff create a new gift transaction for the match and then update the Matching Employer Transaction field on the original donation to link the two records together.\n- **Tribute & Memorial Gifts** [Soft Credits]: Tracks gifts made in honor or memory of another person. Tribute and memorial gifts allow donors to make donations in honor or memory of another person. The Gift Tribute object captures the honoree's name, notification channel, notification contact, notification date, and notification status. Multiple tribute records can be related to a gift commitment or gift transaction, supporting scenarios where a single donation honors multiple people.\n- **Campaign Management** [Campaigns & Outreach]: Creates and manages fundraising campaigns with status tracking, budgets, expected revenue, and date ranges. Campaign Management in Nonprofit Cloud uses the standard Salesforce Campaign object with additional fundraising-specific workflows. The Donor Engagement app provides quick access to track and manage mass market fundraising efforts, grouping engagement data like campaigns, source codes, gift commitments, and reports to make managing outreach efforts fast and effective.\n- **Outreach Source Codes** [Campaigns & Outreach]: Child records of campaigns that provide granular tracking across channel, message, and audience combinations. Outreach Source Codes are child records of campaigns that provide granular attribution below the campaign level. Each source code captures the communication channel used (email, direct mail, social media, phone, web), the specific message or creative that was sent, and the audience segment that was targeted. This three-dimensional tracking enables organizations to determine exactly which combination of channel, message, and audience drives the highest fundraising return.\n- **Campaign Attribution** [Campaigns & Outreach]: Links donations and commitments back to the campaigns that generated them. Campaign attribution connects every donation and commitment back to the fundraising effort that generated it. The campaign field on gift transactions, gift commitments, and opportunities creates a direct link, while outreach source codes provide finer-grained attribution within each campaign. This dual-level attribution enables both high-level campaign performance comparison and detailed channel-by-channel analysis.\n- **Campaign Performance** [Campaigns & Outreach]: Measures and reports on campaign effectiveness through metrics at both the campaign and source code levels. Campaign performance measurement relies on Data Processing Engine to aggregate gift data into meaningful metrics. The OutreachSummary DPE definition calculates totals at both the campaign and source code levels, including total raised, donor count, response rate, and other key performance indicators. These rollups appear on the Related Records Detail Display component on Campaign and Outreach Source Code pages.\n- **Programs** [Program Management]: Defines the programs your organization offers. Programs in Nonprofit Cloud define the structured services and offerings your organization provides to constituents. Each program record captures the name, summary description, active status, and date range. Programs can represent any type of mission-driven service: educational initiatives, food distribution, housing assistance, job readiness training, health services, animal rescue, elder care, environmental cleanup, or community youth programs.\n- **Benefits & Services** [Program Management]: Defines the specific services or goods delivered by a program. Benefits define the specific services or goods that a program delivers to participants. Each benefit has a type classification (Coaching, Distribution, Training, Assessment, or custom types), a unit of measure (Hours, Sessions, Meals, Items), and an active status. Benefits link to the parent program and accumulate disbursement data showing total service delivery volume over time.\n- **Program Enrollment** [Program Management]: Tracks participant registration and status for each program. Program Enrollment records track each participant's registration and lifecycle status within a program. Each enrollment links a constituent account to a program with a status workflow that progresses through Applied, Enrolled, Active, Completed, or Withdrawn. The enrollment date, completion date, and referral source are captured to support program effectiveness analysis and participant flow reporting.\n- **Benefit Disbursement** [Program Management]: Records the actual delivery of services and goods to participants. Benefit Disbursements record the actual delivery of services and goods to program participants. Each record captures the beneficiary account, the benefit being delivered, the quantity in the benefit's unit of measure, the delivery date, and the status (Scheduled, Delivered, Missed, Canceled). Disbursement tracking supports both pre-scheduled service delivery and ad hoc disbursements for walk-in recipients not pre-enrolled in a program.\n- **Goal Definitions** [Program Management]: Creates hierarchical goal structures that define desired outcomes for program participants. Goal Definitions create hierarchical goal structures that map your organization's theory of change from activities to outputs to ultimate impact. Top-level goals decompose into intermediate goals through the parent goal lookup, creating a structured framework that connects program activities to measurable outcomes. Each goal has a name, description, target date, and status (Not Started, In Progress, Achieved, Not Achieved).\n- **Case Referral Intake** [Case Management]: Processes inbound and outbound participant referrals using guided flows. Case Referral Intake provides tools for processing inbound and outbound participant referrals, converting them to cases for assessment and follow-up. Guided flows streamline the intake process, capturing participant information, presenting needs, and urgency level. Referrals can come from partner agencies, self-referral, community sources, or internal staff transfers.\n- **Care Plans** [Case Management]: Creates personalized, goal-oriented plans for program participants. Care Plans provide a way to create, manage, and share personalized plans to help program participants reach their goals. Each plan starts from a standardized Care Plan Template that defines pre-configured benefits and goals, which case managers then customize to the participant's specific needs. Templates can be created for common scenarios such as housing assistance, job readiness, substance recovery, or family services.\n- **Assessments & Discovery** [Case Management]: Discovery Framework provides tools to design and administer structured assessments for program participants. Discovery Framework helps organizations design and organize assessments that evaluate program participants during intake and throughout their participation. Each framework defines the assessment sections, questions, response options, and scoring logic. Multiple frameworks can be created for different assessment types such as needs assessments, periodic reviews, and program-specific evaluations.\n- **Interaction Summaries** [Case Management]: Captures detailed notes from meetings, conversations, and interactions with program participants, donors, caseworkers, and partners. Interaction Summaries provide tools to capture and store detailed notes of meetings and conversations with program participants, donors, caseworkers, advisors, partners, and others. Each summary includes the interaction type, date, participants, detailed notes, and next steps. The confidentiality flag protects sensitive information from unauthorized access, and notes are searchable using smart search and filters.\n- **Outcome Definitions** [Outcome Management]: Describes the intended impact or change your programs aim to achieve. Outcome Definitions describe the intended impact or change that your organization's programs aim to achieve. Each definition articulates what success looks like, identifies the target population, and specifies the measurement timeframe. Outcomes form a hierarchy through parent-child relationships that map your organization's theory of change from activities to outputs to ultimate impact goals.\n- **Indicators** [Outcome Management]: Defines the specific metrics used to measure progress toward outcomes. Indicators define the specific metrics used to measure progress toward each outcome definition. Each indicator specifies what to measure, the data type (number, percent, currency, or text), collection frequency (weekly, monthly, quarterly, or annually), and target and baseline values. This measurement framework supports both quantitative indicators like employment rates and qualitative indicators like participant satisfaction scores.\n- **Indicator Results** [Outcome Management]: Captures actual measurement data points for each indicator over time. Indicator Results capture the actual measurement data points that show whether programs are achieving their intended outcomes. Each result records the measurement date, the measured value, and notes about the collection context. Over time, trending these results reveals the trajectory of program impact and identifies where adjustments are needed to improve effectiveness.\n- **Impact Reporting** [Outcome Management]: Generates reports and dashboards that demonstrate program effectiveness to stakeholders. Impact reporting compiles outcome data, indicator trends, and program metrics into actionable views for different stakeholder audiences. Board presentations highlight organizational-level outcome achievement, donor stewardship reports show how gifts translated into measurable impact by designation, and grant reports demonstrate compliance with funder requirements by tracking progress against funded program outcomes.\n- **Volunteer Initiatives** [Volunteer Management]: Defines volunteer projects and events with start/end dates, headcount goals, and total hours targets. Volunteer Initiatives define the projects, events, and ongoing programs that require volunteer support. Each initiative captures start and end dates, target volunteer count, target total hours, and a description. Initiatives support parent-child hierarchies for large programs with sub-initiatives, enabling organizations to manage complex volunteer programs with multiple components under a single umbrella.\n- **Positions & Job Positions** [Volunteer Management]: Positions define generic volunteer roles (Tutor, Group Leader, Event Coordinator). Positions define generic, reusable volunteer roles that can be applied across multiple initiatives. Each position describes the role requirements, qualifications, and general responsibilities. Examples include Tutor, Group Leader, Event Coordinator, Kitchen Volunteer, and Community Outreach Specialist. Positions provide consistency in role definitions across the organization.\n- **Shifts & Assignments** [Volunteer Management]: Job Position Shifts define specific work periods with start/end times, recurrence schedules, and capacity limits. Job Position Shifts define the specific work periods within each job position, capturing start and end times, recurrence patterns for ongoing roles, and capacity limits for how many volunteers can sign up. Shift management helps coordinators see at a glance which shifts are fully staffed and which still need volunteers, enabling proactive recruiting for open slots.\n- **Volunteer Matching** [Volunteer Management]: Uses smart matching criteria to find the most qualified volunteers for open shifts. Volunteer matching uses a multi-dimensional evaluation of volunteer qualifications to identify the best candidates for open shifts. The matching algorithm considers Person Competencies (skills and certifications the volunteer holds), Person Examination results (tests and screenings they have completed), Person Location Availability (geographic areas where they are willing to serve), and schedule overlap with open shift times.\n- **Volunteer Portal** [Volunteer Management]: An Experience Cloud site where volunteers can browse published initiatives, view position details, sign up for shifts, complete onboarding forms, upload documentation, and track their volunteer hours. The Volunteer Portal is an Experience Cloud site that empowers volunteers to self-serve throughout their engagement lifecycle. Volunteers can browse published initiatives, view position details, sign up for shifts, complete onboarding forms through the Form Framework, upload documentation, and track their volunteer hours. Guest access lets prospective volunteers explore opportunities before creating an account.\n- **Funding Opportunities** [Grantmaking]: Creates and publishes grant opportunities that applicants can discover and apply for. Funding Opportunities define the grants that your organization makes available to applicants. Each opportunity captures the funding amount, application deadline, eligibility criteria, required documentation, and a detailed description. The Is Published flag controls whether the opportunity is visible on the grantee portal, allowing internal preparation before making opportunities public.\n- **Grant Applications** [Grantmaking]: Manages the full lifecycle of grant applications from submission through review to award or decline. Grant Applications manage the complete lifecycle from submission through review to award or decline. Each application captures the applicant organization, requested funding amount, project narrative, and supporting documents. The application status progresses through Draft, Submitted, Under Review, Awarded, or Declined as it moves through the review process.\n- **Grant Budgets & Awards** [Grantmaking]: Tracks proposed and approved budgets for grant applications, then manages award disbursements. Grant Budgets track proposed and approved spending for each grant application. Budget records categorize costs by line item including personnel, direct program costs, overhead, travel, and equipment. Applicants submit budgets as part of their application, and grantmakers review and approve specific line items, potentially adjusting requested amounts before awarding the grant.\n- **Grantee Portal** [Grantmaking]: An Experience Cloud site where grant seekers discover funding opportunities, submit applications, upload documentation, track application status, and report on funded activities. The Grantee Portal is an Experience Cloud site that provides a self-service interface for the entire grant lifecycle. Grant seekers can discover published funding opportunities, review eligibility criteria, submit applications through structured forms, upload supporting documentation, and track the status of their submissions. After receiving an award, grantees use the portal to report on funded activities and outcomes.\n- **AI Gift Proposals** [Agentforce & Einstein AI]: Einstein Copilot generates personalized gift proposals for major donors by analyzing the donor's giving history, interests, and relationship with your organization. Einstein Copilot uses data in your Salesforce org to produce draft gift proposals for major donor solicitations. Major gift officers write proposals that appeal to high-net-worth donors and showcase the impact of their contributions while communicating the organization's mission and tone. Writing these proposals is time-consuming and difficult, so Copilot Actions for Fundraising Gift Proposals streamlines the process using Einstein generative AI and your organization's data.\n- **Einstein Summaries** [Agentforce & Einstein AI]: Generates AI-powered summaries across multiple Nonprofit Cloud areas. Einstein Generative AI produces four types of summaries in Nonprofit Cloud. Einstein Program and Benefits Summary drafts summaries that accurately describe program progress to stakeholders, using data from the Program and Benefits objects. Einstein Notes Summary helps staff quickly absorb information about constituents before meetings, using data from the Account, Interaction, and Interaction Summary objects. Each summary is limited to consuming up to 100 related records as grounding data.\n- **Volunteer AI Agent** [Agentforce & Einstein AI]: An Agentforce agent that assists with volunteer management processes. The Volunteer Management Agent efficiently manages volunteer shifts and initiatives, reducing administrative tasks and improving engagement. The Shift Capacity and Coverage topic in the Agent Builder identifies unfilled shifts and finds the most suitable volunteers to fill them based on qualifications, availability, and location. This agent requires the Einstein for Nonprofits license and the Manage Volunteer Data permission set.\n- **Fundraising AI Agent** [Agentforce & Einstein AI]: Agentforce capabilities for fundraising operations including philanthropic research topics, donor support for commitment management, and participant management automation. Agentforce for Nonprofit Cloud includes several agent topics for fundraising and program management. Philanthropic Research Topics optimize philanthropic engagement and research efforts, helping staff tailor outreach, build personalized engagement strategies, and foster deeper relationships with donors. The Participant Management Agent helps case managers and program staff record benefits, create tasks, and update goals for participants.\n- **Action Plan Templates** [Action Plans]: Defines reusable sequences of tasks for common business processes. Action Plan Templates define the required tasks for completing a business process, creating reusable playbooks that ensure consistent execution across the organization. Each template item specifies the task name, description, default assignee, priority level, number of days from plan start until due, and any dependency on another item. Templates can be created for donor stewardship sequences, volunteer onboarding checklists, program enrollment workflows, case management protocols, and grant review processes.\n- **Action Plan Execution** [Action Plans]: Creates action plan instances from templates and manages task completion. When an action plan is applied to a record such as an opportunity, volunteer initiative, or case, the system generates concrete task items from the template with calculated due dates based on the plan start date and each item's offset. Each generated task is assigned to the appropriate user and tracks completion status through Not Started, In Progress, and Completed stages.\n- **Stage Management** [Action Plans]: Tracks lifecycle stages for key objects using a configurable stage framework. Stage Management provides a configurable lifecycle framework for tracking the progression of key Nonprofit Cloud objects. It can be applied to Volunteer Initiatives, Job Positions, Job Position Assignments, Job Position Shifts, Positions, and Application Forms. Each stage configuration defines the stages in the progression path and can trigger action plans at transitions, automating follow-up tasks when records advance to new stages.\n- **Permission Set Groups** [Security & Access]: Bundles multiple permission sets into manageable groups for role-based access. Permission Set Groups bundle multiple permission sets into manageable groups for role-based access control. Nonprofit Cloud includes managed permission sets for various features, with key groups including Fundraising_User for general fundraising access, Fundraising_Admin for setup and configuration, and feature-specific permission sets for Program Management, Care Plans, Case Referrals, Outcome Management, Grantmaking, and Volunteer Management.\n- **Permission Set Licenses** [Security & Access]: Controls which Nonprofit Cloud features are available in your org. Permission Set Licenses control which Nonprofit Cloud features are available in the org. Each product area has associated licenses that must be assigned to users before the corresponding permission sets take effect. Nonprofit Cloud includes licenses for Fundraising, Program Management, Volunteer Management, Grantmaking, Outcome Management, and various shared Industries features.\n- **Data Security & Privacy** [Security & Access]: Protects sensitive constituent information through organization-wide sharing defaults, field-level security, and role hierarchies. Whether dealing with sensitive program participant information or financial information about donors, security is key. Nonprofit Cloud includes data security tools such as the Identity Verification feature that help protect participant information, prevent unauthorized use, and comply with data regulations. Organization-wide sharing defaults control baseline access for all users, while field-level security restricts visibility of sensitive fields.\n- **Custom & Muting Permission Sets** [Security & Access]: Enables granular permission customization without modifying default sets. If you customize Nonprofit Cloud features such as adding fields, create a custom permission set rather than modifying managed permission sets. To remove user permissions from the default permission set, create a muting permission set. Then use permission set groups to assign users the managed Nonprofit Cloud permission set alongside your custom and muting permission sets. This approach is an alternative to cloning permission sets and makes sure that users always have the latest default permissions from Salesforce.\n- **Feature Enablement** [Setup & Configuration]: Turns on Nonprofit Cloud product areas through Setup menus. Nonprofit Cloud setup begins with completing prerequisites such as enabling Person Accounts, setting up Data Processing Engine, enabling Actionable Segmentation, Interaction Summaries, Interest Tags, Record Alerts, and Timeline. Each of these shared features provides capabilities used across multiple Nonprofit Cloud product areas.\n- **Fundraising Settings** [Setup & Configuration]: Configures core fundraising behavior including Gift Entry settings, Installment Extension Day Count (window for matching transactions to commitments), Lapsed Unpaid Transaction Count (threshold for lapsed status), Failing Transaction Count (threshold for failing status), and auto-close behavior for recurring commitments. Fundraising Settings configure the core behavior of gift commitment processing. The Installment Extension Day Count specifies the number of days before or after which an unpaid transaction for a gift commitment is marked as another installment. The Lapsed Unpaid Transaction Count sets how many sequentially unpaid installments change a commitment status to Lapsed. The Failing Transaction Count sets how many sequentially failed installments trigger the Failing status.\n- **Data Processing Engine** [Setup & Configuration]: Salesforce's batch data transformation tool that powers automated rollup calculations in Nonprofit Cloud. Data Processing Engine transforms data available in your Salesforce org and uses the results to create or update records. In Nonprofit Cloud, DPE is used to generate rollup field data for both fundraising and programs. The DonorGiftSummary definition calculates comprehensive giving history fields, the GiftDesignation definition aggregates designation totals, and the OutreachSummary definition compiles campaign and source code performance metrics.\n- **Picklists & Record Types** [Setup & Configuration]: Configures picklist values and record types that customize Nonprofit Cloud behavior. Picklists and record types customize Nonprofit Cloud behavior for your organization's specific needs. Key picklist values include Payment Method (Cash, Check, Credit Card, ACH, Wire, Stock), Gift Vehicle types, Commitment Types, Campaign Types, Benefit Types, and Relationship Roles. Admins customize these values to match their organization's terminology and workflows.\n\n## Key Objects (73)\n### Constituents\n- **Account**: Represents both individual and organizational constituents in Nonprofit Cloud.\n- **Contact**: Stores individual-specific information for Person Account constituents.\n- **ContactProfile**: Extends constituent records with fundraising-specific attributes beyond what standard Account and Contact fields provide.\n### Households & Groups\n- **PartyRelationshipGroup**: The container object for modeling households and other constituent group types in Nonprofit Cloud.\n- **AccountContactRelationship**: Links individual Person Accounts to group or organizational Business Accounts with specific roles and date ranges.\n### Relationships\n- **ContactContactRelationship**: Models direct relationships between individuals such as spouse, parent-child, sibling, mentor-mentee, and colleague connections.\n- **AccountAccountRelationship**: Models relationships between organizations such as corporate affiliations, foundation-grantee connections, partner agency ties, and vendor relationships.\n- **PartyRoleRelationship**: Metadata object that defines the available relationship types and their reciprocal labels for use in Contact Contact Relationships and Account Account Relationships.\n### Contact Information\n- **ContactPointAddress**: Stores physical mailing and location addresses for constituents using Salesforce's polymorphic Contact Point model.\n- **ContactPointEmail**: Stores email addresses for constituents with support for multiple records per person.\n- **ContactPointPhone**: Stores phone numbers for constituents with support for multiple records per person.\n### Fundraising Pipeline\n- **Opportunity**: Tracks major gift solicitations, grant proposals, and significant fundraising asks moving through a configurable pipeline.\n- **OpportunityContactRole**: Associates multiple constituents with an opportunity and defines each person's role in the solicitation.\n### Gift Commitments\n- **GiftCommitment**: Represents a donor's promise to give through pledges, recurring donations, or multi-payment gift agreements.\n- **GiftCommitmentSchedule**: Defines the installment pattern for a gift commitment including frequency, interval, day of month, effective dates, and amount per installment.\n- **GiftCommitmentChangeAttributionLog**: Records every modification to a gift commitment for audit and attribution purposes.\n### Gift Transactions\n- **GiftTransaction**: Tracks every received gift and payment as a discrete transaction record in Nonprofit Cloud.\n- **PaymentInstrument**: Stores donor payment method information such as credit card last four digits, expiration dates, and ACH bank account details.\n### Gift Entry & Processing\n- **GiftEntry**: A staging record that captures gift information before it is processed into a Gift Transaction.\n- **GiftBatch**: Groups gift entries for bulk processing with validation and error handling.\n- **GiftBatchTemplate**: Defines the field layout and configuration for gift entry batches and the single gift entry window.\n### Gift Designations\n- **GiftDesignation**: Represents a named funding purpose that donors can direct their gifts toward, such as General Fund, Scholarship Fund, or Building Campaign.\n- **GiftTransactionDesignation**: Junction object that links gift transactions to gift designations with a percentage or amount allocation.\n- **GiftDefaultDesignation**: Manages the inheritance hierarchy that automatically assigns designations to gifts when no explicit allocation is provided.\n### Soft Credits\n- **GiftSoftCredit**: Records attribution for constituents who influenced or facilitated a donation without being the primary donor.\n### Campaigns & Outreach\n- **Campaign**: Manages fundraising campaigns with status tracking, budgets, expected revenue, and date ranges.\n- **OutreachSourceCode**: Child records of campaigns that provide granular tracking across channel, message, and audience combinations.\n### Program Management\n- **Program**: Defines a structured program or service offering that the nonprofit delivers to its constituents.\n- **Benefit**: Defines a specific service or good delivered by a program, such as counseling sessions, food packages, job training hours, or educational materials.\n- **BenefitType**: Categorizes benefits into types such as Coaching, Distribution, Training, Assessment, or Shelter.\n- **UnitOfMeasure**: Defines the measurement unit for tracking benefit delivery quantities such as Hours, Sessions, Meals, Items, or Dollars.\n- **ProgramEnrollment**: Tracks participant registration and lifecycle status for each program.\n- **ProgramCohort**: Groups program participants into cohorts for session management, reporting, and comparative analysis.\n- **ProgramCohortMember**: Junction object linking a participant to a specific program cohort.\n- **BenefitDisbursement**: Records the actual delivery of services and goods to program participants.\n- **BenefitSchedule**: Defines when and how often a benefit is delivered to participants.\n- **BenefitSession**: Represents a single occurrence of a scheduled benefit delivery, such as one tutoring session, one meal distribution event, or one training class.\n- **BenefitAssignment**: Links a specific participant to a benefit they are expected to receive, enabling targeted service delivery tracking.\n- **GoalDefinition**: Creates hierarchical goal structures that define desired outcomes for program participants.\n### Case Management\n- **Case**: The core case management object tracking participant needs, referrals, and service coordination.\n- **CarePlan**: A personalized, goal-oriented plan created for a program participant by their case manager.\n- **CarePlanTemplate**: Defines a reusable care plan starting point with pre-configured benefits and goals for common participant scenarios.\n- **CarePlanTemplateBenefit**: Links a benefit to a care plan template, specifying which services should be included when the template is used to create a new care plan.\n- **CarePlanTemplateGoal**: Links a goal definition to a care plan template, specifying which outcomes should be tracked when the template creates a new care plan.\n- **CaseReferral**: Tracks inbound and outbound participant referrals between organizations and internal departments.\n- **AssessmentTask**: Represents a structured assessment administered to a program participant using the Discovery Framework.\n- **DiscoveryFramework**: Defines the structure and questions for participant assessments.\n- **InteractionSummary**: Captures detailed notes from meetings, conversations, and interactions with program participants, donors, caseworkers, and partners.\n### Outcome Management\n- **OutcomeDefinition**: Describes the intended impact or change that programs aim to achieve.\n- **Indicator**: Defines a specific metric used to measure progress toward an outcome.\n- **IndicatorResult**: Captures an actual measurement data point for an indicator at a specific point in time.\n### Volunteer Management\n- **VolunteerInitiative**: Defines a volunteer project, event, or ongoing program with start and end dates, headcount goals, and total hours targets.\n- **Position**: Defines a generic volunteer role that can be reused across multiple initiatives.\n- **JobPosition**: Customizes a generic Position for a specific Volunteer Initiative with shift schedules, location, qualifications, and approval requirements.\n- **JobPositionShift**: Defines a specific work period within a job position with start and end times, recurrence schedules, and capacity limits.\n- **JobPositionAssignment**: Links a volunteer to a specific job position shift with status tracking through the assignment lifecycle.\n- **Competency**: Defines a skill, qualification, or expertise area that can be required for volunteer positions and tracked for individual volunteers.\n- **PersonCompetency**: Links an individual volunteer to a competency they possess, including the proficiency level, date achieved, and expiration date if applicable.\n- **Examination**: Defines a test, certification exam, or screening that volunteers may need to complete.\n- **PersonExamination**: Records an individual volunteer's attempt at an examination, capturing the score, pass/fail result, and completion date.\n- **PersonLocationAvailability**: Records a volunteer's geographic availability and preferred work locations.\n### Grantmaking\n- **FundingOpportunity**: Creates and publishes grant opportunities that applicants can discover and apply for through Experience Cloud portals.\n- **GrantApplication**: Manages the full lifecycle of a grant application from submission through review to award or decline.\n- **ApplicationReview**: Records an internal evaluator's assessment of a grant application.\n- **Budget**: Tracks proposed and approved budget details for grant applications.\n- **FundingAward**: Represents an approved grant award with the approved amount, disbursement schedule, and reporting requirements.\n### Action Plans\n- **ActionPlan**: An instance of an action plan created from a template and applied to a specific record such as an opportunity, case, or volunteer initiative.\n- **ActionPlanTemplate**: Defines a reusable sequence of tasks for common business processes.\n- **ActionPlanTemplateItem**: Defines a single task within an action plan template.\n- **ActionPlanItem**: A generated task instance within an action plan, created from a template item.\n- **StageDefinition**: Defines lifecycle stages for key objects using a configurable stage framework.\n### Security & Access\n- **PermissionSetGroup**: Bundles multiple permission sets into manageable groups for role-based access control.\n- **PermissionSetLicense**: Controls which Nonprofit Cloud features are available in the org by extending platform capabilities with product-specific licenses.\n\n## Custom Metadata Types (4)\n### Fundraising Pipeline\n- **FundraisingSetting__mdt** (Fundraising Settings): Configures core fundraising behavior including the installment extension window for matching transactions to commitments, lapsed and failing status thresholds for recurring commitments, and auto-close behavior.\n### Program Management\n- **ProgramManagementSetting__mdt** (Program Management Settings): Configures program management behavior including automatic enrollment processing, default benefit type for new benefits, disbursement tracking activation, and maximum depth for goal definition hierarchies.\n### Setup & Configuration\n- **NonprofitCloudSetting__mdt** (Nonprofit Cloud Settings): Master configuration for enabling and disabling Nonprofit Cloud product areas.\n- **DataProcessingEngineDefinition__mdt** (Data Processing Engine Definitions): Configures Data Processing Engine batch jobs that power automated rollup calculations across Nonprofit Cloud.\n\n## Object Fields\n### Account (6 fields)\n- Name (Text): Account name; auto-populated from first/last name for Person Accounts\n- RecordTypeId (Lookup): Distinguishes Person Accounts from Business Accounts\n- ParentId (Lookup): Parent account for modeling organizational hierarchies\n- Type (Picklist): Account classification such as Donor, Foundation, Partner, or Vendor\n- BillingAddress (Text): Primary billing address compound field\n- Phone (Phone): Primary phone number for the account\n### Contact (5 fields)\n- FirstName (Text): Individual's first name\n- LastName (Text): Individual's last name\n- Email (Email): Primary email address\n- Birthdate (Date): Date of birth for age-based segmentation and reporting\n- AccountId (Lookup): The Account this Contact is associated with\n### ContactProfile (4 fields)\n- Name (AutoNumber): System-generated profile identifier\n- AccountId (Lookup): The constituent account this profile extends\n- DonorClassification (Picklist): Donor segmentation category such as Major Donor, Mid-Level, or Annual Fund\n- RecurringDonorType (Picklist): Indicates whether the constituent is a sustaining, lapsed, or prospective recurring donor\n### PartyRelationshipGroup (5 fields)\n- Name (Text): Display name for the group, often the household surname\n- Type (Picklist): Group classification such as Household, Affinity Group, or Board\n- AccountId (Lookup): The Business Account that represents this group\n- StartDate (Date): Date when the group was established\n- EndDate (Date): Date when the group was dissolved, if applicable\n### AccountContactRelationship (6 fields)\n- AccountId (Lookup): The organization or group account\n- ContactId (Lookup): The individual contact being linked to the account\n- Roles (MultiPicklist): One or more roles the individual holds in the organization (Head of Household, Member, Board Member)\n- IsActive (Checkbox): Whether the relationship is currently active\n- StartDate (Date): Date when the relationship began\n- EndDate (Date): Date when the relationship ended, if applicable\n### ContactContactRelationship (6 fields)\n- Name (AutoNumber): System-generated relationship identifier\n- ContactId (Lookup): The first individual in the relationship\n- RelatedContactId (Lookup): The second individual in the relationship\n- RoleId (Lookup): The Party Role Relationship defining the type (e.g., Spouse, Parent)\n- IsActive (Checkbox): Whether the relationship is currently active\n- StartDate (Date): Date when the relationship began\n### AccountAccountRelationship (5 fields)\n- Name (AutoNumber): System-generated relationship identifier\n- AccountId (Lookup): The first organization in the relationship\n- RelatedAccountId (Lookup): The second organization in the relationship\n- RoleId (Lookup): The Party Role Relationship defining the relationship type\n- IsActive (Checkbox): Whether the organizational relationship is currently active\n### PartyRoleRelationship (4 fields)\n- Name (Text): Forward-direction label for the relationship (e.g., Parent)\n- ReciprocalLabel (Text): Reverse-direction label (e.g., Child)\n- RelationshipType (Picklist): Category of relationship (Family, Professional, Community)\n- IsActive (Checkbox): Whether this relationship type is available for selection\n### ContactPointAddress (9 fields)\n- Name (Text): Display label for this address record\n- ParentId (Lookup): The Account this address belongs to (polymorphic)\n- AddressType (Picklist): Classification such as Home, Work, Vacation, or Other\n- Street (TextArea): Street address lines\n- City (Text): City name\n- StateCode (Picklist): State or province code\n- PostalCode (Text): Postal or ZIP code\n- CountryCode (Picklist): Country code\n- IsPrimary (Checkbox): Whether this is the preferred mailing address\n### ContactPointEmail (5 fields)\n- Name (Text): Display label for this email record\n- ParentId (Lookup): The Account this email belongs to (polymorphic)\n- EmailAddress (Email): The email address\n- EmailType (Picklist): Classification such as Personal, Work, or Other\n- IsPrimary (Checkbox): Whether this is the preferred email address\n### ContactPointPhone (5 fields)\n- Name (Text): Display label for this phone record\n- ParentId (Lookup): The Account this phone number belongs to (polymorphic)\n- TelephoneNumber (Phone): The phone number\n- PhoneType (Picklist): Classification such as Home, Mobile, Work, or Fax\n- IsPrimary (Checkbox): Whether this is the preferred phone number\n### Opportunity (8 fields)\n- Name (Text): Descriptive name for the solicitation or proposal\n- Amount (Currency): Expected gift amount for the opportunity\n- StageName (Picklist): Current pipeline stage (Prospecting, Cultivation, Solicitation, Closed Won)\n- CloseDate (Date): Expected or actual close date\n- Probability (Percent): Likelihood of winning the opportunity\n- AccountId (Lookup): The donor or organization account\n- CampaignId (Lookup): The campaign that sourced this opportunity\n- RecordTypeId (Lookup): Distinguishes major gifts, grants, planned giving, and other fundraising types\n### OpportunityContactRole (4 fields)\n- OpportunityId (Lookup): The opportunity this contact role belongs to\n- ContactId (Lookup): The individual involved in the opportunity\n- Role (Picklist): The person's role (Primary Donor, Influencer, Decision Maker, Soft Credit)\n- IsPrimary (Checkbox): Whether this is the primary contact for the opportunity\n### GiftCommitment (8 fields)\n- Name (AutoNumber): System-generated commitment identifier\n- AccountId (Lookup): The donor account making the commitment\n- CommitmentType (Picklist): Type of commitment: Recurring or Custom\n- Status (Picklist): Lifecycle status: Draft, Active, Paused, Lapsed, Failing, or Closed\n- TotalAmount (Currency): Total committed amount across all installments\n- CampaignId (Lookup): The campaign that sourced this commitment\n- OpportunityId (Lookup): The originating fundraising opportunity\n- StartDate (Date): Date when the commitment begins\n### GiftCommitmentSchedule (7 fields)\n- Name (AutoNumber): System-generated schedule identifier\n- GiftCommitmentId (Lookup): The parent gift commitment\n- Frequency (Picklist): Installment frequency: Monthly, Quarterly, Annually, or Custom\n- InstallmentAmount (Currency): Amount per installment payment\n- DayOfMonth (Number): Day of the month on which installments are due\n- EffectiveStartDate (Date): Date when this schedule becomes active\n- EffectiveEndDate (Date): Date when this schedule stops generating transactions\n### GiftCommitmentChangeAttributionLog (7 fields)\n- Name (AutoNumber): System-generated log entry identifier\n- GiftCommitmentId (Lookup): The commitment that was changed\n- ChangeType (Picklist): Type of change: Upgrade, Downgrade, Pause, Resume, Payment Method Change\n- PerDayAmountChange (Currency): Daily amount impact of the change for ROI calculation\n- CampaignId (Lookup): The campaign that influenced this change\n- OutreachSourceCodeId (Lookup): The specific outreach source code that drove the change\n- ChangeDate (DateTime): Timestamp when the change was made\n### GiftTransaction (12 fields)\n- Name (AutoNumber): System-generated transaction identifier\n- AccountId (Lookup): The donor account for this transaction\n- Amount (Currency): Transaction amount received or expected\n- Status (Picklist): Transaction lifecycle: Unpaid, Pending, Paid, Failed, Canceled, Refunded, Written Off\n- GiftReceivedDate (Date): Date the gift was received\n- PaymentMethod (Picklist): How the donor paid: Credit Card, Check, ACH, Wire, Cash\n- GiftVehicle (Picklist): Gift type: Cash, Check, Credit Card, Stock, Wire Transfer, In-Kind\n- GiftCommitmentId (Lookup): The commitment this transaction fulfills, if applicable\n- CampaignId (Lookup): Campaign attribution for this transaction\n- OutreachSourceCodeId (Lookup): Granular outreach source code for attribution\n- AcknowledgmentStatus (Picklist): Whether the donor has been thanked: Not Sent, Sent, Failed\n- MatchingEmployerTransactionId (Lookup): Links to the corporate matching gift transaction\n### PaymentInstrument (6 fields)\n- Name (Text): Display name for the payment method (e.g., Visa ending 4242)\n- AccountId (Lookup): The donor account that owns this payment instrument\n- PaymentType (Picklist): Type of payment: Credit Card, ACH, Bank Transfer\n- LastFourDigits (Text): Last four digits of the card or account number\n- ExpirationDate (Date): Expiration date for credit card instruments\n- IsActive (Checkbox): Whether this payment instrument is currently active\n### GiftEntry (7 fields)\n- Name (AutoNumber): System-generated entry identifier\n- DonorAccountId (Lookup): The donor account for this gift entry\n- Amount (Currency): Gift amount to be processed\n- PaymentMethod (Picklist): How the donor is paying\n- GiftBatchId (Lookup): The batch this entry belongs to, if applicable\n- ProcessingStatus (Picklist): Entry status: Draft, Ready, Processing, Completed, Failed\n- ProcessingResult (LongTextArea): Processing outcome details including any error messages\n### GiftBatch (6 fields)\n- Name (Text): Descriptive name for the batch\n- GiftBatchTemplateId (Lookup): The template controlling which fields appear in the batch\n- ExpectedGiftCount (Number): Expected number of gifts for reconciliation\n- EstimatedValue (Currency): Expected total value for reconciliation\n- Status (Picklist): Batch status: Open, Processing, Completed, Partially Processed\n- ProcessedDate (DateTime): Timestamp when the batch was processed\n### GiftBatchTemplate (4 fields)\n- Name (Text): Template name describing its purpose\n- Description (LongTextArea): Explanation of when to use this template\n- FieldConfiguration (LongTextArea): JSON configuration of fields, order, and defaults\n- IsActive (Checkbox): Whether this template is available for use\n### GiftDesignation (6 fields)\n- Name (Text): Fund or purpose name displayed to donors and staff\n- IsActive (Checkbox): Whether this designation is available for gift allocation\n- IsDefault (Checkbox): Whether this is the org-wide default designation for unrestricted gifts\n- TotalAmount (Currency): Rollup total of all allocated gift transaction amounts\n- TransactionCount (Number): Rollup count of gift transactions allocated to this designation\n- Description (LongTextArea): Description of the fund's purpose and restrictions\n### GiftTransactionDesignation (5 fields)\n- Name (AutoNumber): System-generated allocation identifier\n- GiftTransactionId (Lookup): The gift transaction being allocated\n- GiftDesignationId (Lookup): The designation receiving the allocation\n- Amount (Currency): Dollar amount allocated to this designation\n- Percent (Percent): Percentage of the transaction allocated to this designation\n### GiftDefaultDesignation (4 fields)\n- Name (AutoNumber): System-generated default designation identifier\n- GiftDesignationId (Lookup): The designation to use as the default\n- ParentRecordId (Lookup): The campaign, commitment, or opportunity this default applies to (polymorphic)\n- Priority (Number): Priority level in the inheritance hierarchy\n### GiftSoftCredit (6 fields)\n- Name (AutoNumber): System-generated soft credit identifier\n- GiftTransactionId (Lookup): The gift transaction being credited\n- AccountId (Lookup): The constituent account receiving the soft credit\n- CreditType (Picklist): Type of credit: Influence, Tribute, Solicitation, Household Member, Matching\n- Amount (Currency): Amount of the soft credit, which may be partial\n- Description (TextArea): Notes about why this credit was given\n### Campaign (8 fields)\n- Name (Text): Campaign name\n- Type (Picklist): Campaign type: Appeal, Event, Direct Mail, Digital, Phonathon\n- Status (Picklist): Campaign lifecycle: Planned, In Progress, Completed, Aborted\n- StartDate (Date): Campaign start date\n- EndDate (Date): Campaign end date\n- BudgetedCost (Currency): Planned budget for the campaign\n- ExpectedRevenue (Currency): Expected total revenue from the campaign\n- ActualCost (Currency): Actual cost incurred\n### OutreachSourceCode (6 fields)\n- Name (Text): Source code identifier, often a formatted tracking code\n- CampaignId (Lookup): The parent campaign\n- Channel (Picklist): Communication channel: Email, Direct Mail, Social, Phone, Web\n- Message (Text): Specific message or creative identifier\n- Audience (Text): Target audience segment description\n- IsActive (Checkbox): Whether this source code is active for attribution\n### Program (5 fields)\n- Name (Text): Program name\n- Summary (LongTextArea): Detailed description of the program's purpose and activities\n- Status (Picklist): Program lifecycle: Active, Inactive, Planned, Completed\n- StartDate (Date): Date when the program begins operations\n- EndDate (Date): Date when the program concludes, if applicable\n### Benefit (5 fields)\n- Name (Text): Benefit name describing the service or good\n- ProgramId (Lookup): The program that offers this benefit\n- BenefitTypeId (Lookup): The type category: Coaching, Distribution, Training, etc.\n- UnitOfMeasureId (Lookup): The unit used to measure delivery quantity\n- IsActive (Checkbox): Whether this benefit is currently offered\n### BenefitType (3 fields)\n- Name (Text): Type name such as Coaching, Distribution, or Training\n- Description (LongTextArea): Explanation of what this benefit type covers\n- IsActive (Checkbox): Whether this type is available for classifying benefits\n### UnitOfMeasure (3 fields)\n- Name (Text): Unit name such as Hours, Sessions, Meals, or Items\n- Abbreviation (Text): Short form of the unit (e.g., hrs, qty)\n- IsActive (Checkbox): Whether this unit is available for use\n### ProgramEnrollment (6 fields)\n- Name (AutoNumber): System-generated enrollment identifier\n- AccountId (Lookup): The participant account\n- ProgramId (Lookup): The program the participant is enrolling in\n- Status (Picklist): Enrollment status: Applied, Enrolled, Active, Completed, Withdrawn\n- EnrollmentDate (Date): Date when the participant enrolled\n- CompletionDate (Date): Date when the participant completed or withdrew\n### ProgramCohort (5 fields)\n- Name (Text): Cohort name or identifier\n- ProgramId (Lookup): The program this cohort belongs to\n- StartDate (Date): Cohort start date\n- EndDate (Date): Cohort end date\n- Capacity (Number): Maximum number of participants in this cohort\n### ProgramCohortMember (4 fields)\n- Name (AutoNumber): System-generated member identifier\n- ProgramCohortId (Lookup): The cohort this member belongs to\n- AccountId (Lookup): The participant account\n- Status (Picklist): Membership status: Active, Inactive, Completed\n### BenefitDisbursement (6 fields)\n- Name (AutoNumber): System-generated disbursement identifier\n- AccountId (Lookup): The participant receiving the benefit\n- BenefitId (Lookup): The benefit being delivered\n- Quantity (Number): Amount delivered in the benefit's unit of measure\n- DisbursementDate (Date): Date of service delivery\n- Status (Picklist): Delivery status: Scheduled, Delivered, Missed, Canceled\n### BenefitSchedule (5 fields)\n- Name (Text): Schedule name describing the delivery pattern\n- BenefitId (Lookup): The benefit this schedule applies to\n- Frequency (Picklist): Delivery frequency: Daily, Weekly, Biweekly, Monthly\n- StartDate (Date): Schedule start date\n- EndDate (Date): Schedule end date\n### BenefitSession (5 fields)\n- Name (Text): Session name or date identifier\n- BenefitScheduleId (Lookup): The schedule that generated this session\n- SessionDate (DateTime): Date and time of the session\n- Location (Text): Where the session takes place\n- Status (Picklist): Session status: Scheduled, In Progress, Completed, Canceled\n### BenefitAssignment (5 fields)\n- Name (AutoNumber): System-generated assignment identifier\n- AccountId (Lookup): The participant assigned to receive this benefit\n- BenefitId (Lookup): The benefit the participant is assigned to receive\n- AssignedQuantity (Number): Total quantity the participant is expected to receive\n- Status (Picklist): Assignment status: Active, Completed, Suspended\n### GoalDefinition (5 fields)\n- Name (Text): Goal name describing the desired outcome\n- Description (LongTextArea): Detailed description of the goal and success criteria\n- ParentGoalId (Lookup): Parent goal for hierarchical goal structures\n- TargetDate (Date): Date by which the goal should be achieved\n- Status (Picklist): Goal status: Not Started, In Progress, Achieved, Not Achieved\n### Case (8 fields)\n- CaseNumber (AutoNumber): System-generated case identifier\n- Subject (Text): Brief description of the case subject\n- Status (Picklist): Case lifecycle: New, In Progress, Pending, Closed\n- Priority (Picklist): Urgency level: Low, Medium, High, Critical\n- AccountId (Lookup): The participant account\n- ContactId (Lookup): The participant contact\n- Origin (Picklist): How the case was created: Self-Referral, Partner Agency, Internal, Phone\n- Description (LongTextArea): Detailed description of the participant's needs\n### CarePlan (7 fields)\n- Name (Text): Care plan name describing its focus area\n- AccountId (Lookup): The participant account this plan serves\n- CaseId (Lookup): The case this care plan addresses\n- CarePlanTemplateId (Lookup): The template used as a starting point\n- Status (Picklist): Plan status: Draft, Active, Completed, Discontinued\n- StartDate (Date): Plan start date\n- EndDate (Date): Plan end date\n### CarePlanTemplate (3 fields)\n- Name (Text): Template name describing the scenario it addresses\n- Description (LongTextArea): Detailed description of when to use this template\n- IsActive (Checkbox): Whether this template is available for use\n### CarePlanTemplateBenefit (4 fields)\n- Name (AutoNumber): System-generated identifier\n- CarePlanTemplateId (Lookup): The parent care plan template\n- BenefitId (Lookup): The benefit to include in the plan\n- RecommendedQuantity (Number): Suggested delivery quantity for this benefit\n### CarePlanTemplateGoal (4 fields)\n- Name (AutoNumber): System-generated identifier\n- CarePlanTemplateId (Lookup): The parent care plan template\n- GoalDefinitionId (Lookup): The goal to include in the plan\n- TargetDays (Number): Recommended number of days to achieve this goal\n### CaseReferral (6 fields)\n- Name (AutoNumber): System-generated referral identifier\n- CaseId (Lookup): The case created from or associated with this referral\n- ReferralType (Picklist): Direction: Inbound or Outbound\n- ReferringOrganization (Text): The organization making the referral\n- Reason (TextArea): Why the participant is being referred\n- Status (Picklist): Referral status: Pending, Accepted, Declined, Completed\n### AssessmentTask (6 fields)\n- Name (Text): Assessment name or type\n- AccountId (Lookup): The participant being assessed\n- DiscoveryFrameworkId (Lookup): The assessment framework used\n- Status (Picklist): Assessment status: Not Started, In Progress, Completed\n- Score (Number): Calculated assessment score\n- CompletedDate (DateTime): When the assessment was completed\n### DiscoveryFramework (4 fields)\n- Name (Text): Framework name describing the assessment type\n- Description (LongTextArea): Purpose and usage instructions for this framework\n- IsActive (Checkbox): Whether this framework is available for use\n- ScoringMethod (Picklist): How scores are calculated: Sum, Average, Weighted\n### InteractionSummary (7 fields)\n- Name (Text): Interaction title or subject\n- AccountId (Lookup): The account this interaction relates to\n- InteractionType (Picklist): Type: Meeting, Phone Call, Email, Home Visit, Group Session\n- InteractionDate (DateTime): When the interaction took place\n- Notes (RichTextArea): Detailed notes from the interaction\n- NextSteps (LongTextArea): Planned follow-up actions\n- IsConfidential (Checkbox): Whether this interaction contains sensitive information requiring restricted access\n### OutcomeDefinition (5 fields)\n- Name (Text): Outcome name describing the desired impact\n- Description (LongTextArea): Detailed description of the outcome and its significance\n- TargetPopulation (Text): The group of people this outcome applies to\n- ParentOutcomeId (Lookup): Parent outcome for hierarchical theory of change\n- IsActive (Checkbox): Whether this outcome definition is currently tracked\n### Indicator (6 fields)\n- Name (Text): Indicator name describing the metric\n- OutcomeDefinitionId (Lookup): The outcome this indicator measures\n- DataType (Picklist): Data type: Number, Percent, Currency, Text\n- CollectionFrequency (Picklist): How often data is collected: Weekly, Monthly, Quarterly, Annually\n- TargetValue (Number): The target value that represents success\n- BaselineValue (Number): Starting value before program intervention\n### IndicatorResult (5 fields)\n- Name (AutoNumber): System-generated result identifier\n- IndicatorId (Lookup): The indicator this result measures\n- ResultValue (Number): The measured value\n- MeasurementDate (Date): Date when the measurement was taken\n- CollectionContext (TextArea): Notes about how and where the data was collected\n### VolunteerInitiative (9 fields)\n- Name (Text): Initiative name\n- Description (LongTextArea): Detailed description of the volunteer project\n- StartDate (Date): Initiative start date\n- EndDate (Date): Initiative end date\n- Status (Picklist): Initiative status: Planned, Active, Completed, Canceled\n- TargetVolunteerCount (Number): Target number of volunteers needed\n- TargetHours (Number): Target total volunteer hours\n- ParentInitiativeId (Lookup): Parent initiative for hierarchical structures\n- IsPublished (Checkbox): Whether this initiative is visible on the volunteer portal\n### Position (4 fields)\n- Name (Text): Position title\n- Description (LongTextArea): Role description and general responsibilities\n- RequiredQualifications (LongTextArea): Qualifications needed for this role\n- IsActive (Checkbox): Whether this position is available for use\n### JobPosition (6 fields)\n- Name (Text): Job position name specific to this initiative\n- VolunteerInitiativeId (Lookup): The initiative this job position belongs to\n- PositionId (Lookup): The generic position this job position instantiates\n- Location (Text): Where the volunteer will work\n- RequiresApproval (Checkbox): Whether signup requires manager approval\n- HeadcountTarget (Number): Number of volunteers needed for this job position\n### JobPositionShift (6 fields)\n- Name (Text): Shift name or time slot description\n- JobPositionId (Lookup): The job position this shift belongs to\n- StartDateTime (DateTime): Shift start date and time\n- EndDateTime (DateTime): Shift end date and time\n- Capacity (Number): Maximum number of volunteers for this shift\n- FilledCount (Number): Number of volunteers currently assigned\n### JobPositionAssignment (5 fields)\n- Name (AutoNumber): System-generated assignment identifier\n- JobPositionShiftId (Lookup): The shift this volunteer is assigned to\n- AccountId (Lookup): The volunteer's person account\n- Status (Picklist): Assignment status: Upcoming, In Progress, Completed, No Show, Canceled\n- ActualHours (Number): Actual hours worked by the volunteer\n### Competency (4 fields)\n- Name (Text): Competency name\n- Description (LongTextArea): What this competency represents\n- Category (Picklist): Competency category: Skill, Certification, License, Background Check\n- IsActive (Checkbox): Whether this competency is actively tracked\n### PersonCompetency (6 fields)\n- Name (AutoNumber): System-generated identifier\n- AccountId (Lookup): The volunteer who holds this competency\n- CompetencyId (Lookup): The competency being recorded\n- ProficiencyLevel (Picklist): Proficiency: Beginner, Intermediate, Advanced, Expert\n- DateAchieved (Date): When the volunteer earned this competency\n- ExpirationDate (Date): When the competency expires, if applicable\n### Examination (5 fields)\n- Name (Text): Examination name\n- Description (LongTextArea): What this examination covers and how it is administered\n- PassingScore (Number): Minimum score required to pass\n- ValidityPeriod (Number): Number of months the result remains valid\n- IsActive (Checkbox): Whether this examination is currently in use\n### PersonExamination (7 fields)\n- Name (AutoNumber): System-generated identifier\n- AccountId (Lookup): The volunteer who took the examination\n- ExaminationId (Lookup): The examination that was taken\n- Score (Number): Score achieved on the examination\n- Passed (Checkbox): Whether the volunteer passed\n- CompletedDate (Date): Date the examination was completed\n- ExpirationDate (Date): Date when this result expires\n### PersonLocationAvailability (5 fields)\n- Name (Text): Location description\n- AccountId (Lookup): The volunteer who is available at this location\n- City (Text): City where the volunteer is available\n- State (Text): State or province\n- MaxDistanceMiles (Number): Maximum distance the volunteer is willing to travel\n### FundingOpportunity (7 fields)\n- Name (Text): Funding opportunity title\n- Description (RichTextArea): Detailed description of the funding opportunity\n- FundingAmount (Currency): Total funding available for this opportunity\n- ApplicationDeadline (DateTime): Last date to submit applications\n- EligibilityCriteria (LongTextArea): Requirements applicants must meet\n- Status (Picklist): Opportunity status: Draft, Open, Closed, Awarded\n- IsPublished (Checkbox): Whether visible on the grantee portal\n### GrantApplication (7 fields)\n- Name (AutoNumber): System-generated application identifier\n- FundingOpportunityId (Lookup): The funding opportunity being applied for\n- ApplicantAccountId (Lookup): The organization submitting the application\n- RequestedAmount (Currency): Amount of funding requested\n- ProjectNarrative (RichTextArea): Description of the proposed project\n- Status (Picklist): Application status: Draft, Submitted, Under Review, Awarded, Declined\n- SubmittedDate (DateTime): When the application was submitted\n### ApplicationReview (6 fields)\n- Name (AutoNumber): System-generated review identifier\n- GrantApplicationId (Lookup): The application being reviewed\n- ReviewerId (Lookup): The user performing the review\n- Score (Number): Numeric evaluation score\n- Comments (RichTextArea): Qualitative assessment comments\n- Recommendation (Picklist): Reviewer recommendation: Approve, Decline, Revise and Resubmit\n### Budget (6 fields)\n- Name (Text): Budget name or category\n- GrantApplicationId (Lookup): The application this budget belongs to\n- Category (Picklist): Budget category: Personnel, Direct Costs, Overhead, Travel, Equipment\n- RequestedAmount (Currency): Amount requested for this budget line\n- ApprovedAmount (Currency): Amount approved for this budget line\n- Justification (LongTextArea): Narrative explaining why this cost is necessary\n### FundingAward (7 fields)\n- Name (AutoNumber): System-generated award identifier\n- GrantApplicationId (Lookup): The approved application\n- AccountId (Lookup): The grantee organization account\n- AwardAmount (Currency): Total approved funding amount\n- AwardDate (Date): Date the award was granted\n- Status (Picklist): Award status: Active, Completed, Suspended, Terminated\n- DisbursedAmount (Currency): Total amount disbursed to date\n### ActionPlan (6 fields)\n- Name (Text): Action plan name, usually derived from the template\n- ActionPlanTemplateId (Lookup): The template used to create this plan\n- TargetId (Lookup): The record this plan is applied to (polymorphic: Opportunity, Case, Initiative)\n- Status (Picklist): Plan status: Not Started, In Progress, Completed\n- StartDate (Date): Date the plan was initiated\n- CompletionPercentage (Percent): Percentage of tasks completed\n### ActionPlanTemplate (4 fields)\n- Name (Text): Template name describing the process\n- Description (LongTextArea): Detailed description of when to use this template\n- TargetObjectType (Picklist): Object type this template applies to: Opportunity, Case, Initiative\n- IsActive (Checkbox): Whether this template is available for use\n### ActionPlanTemplateItem (6 fields)\n- Name (Text): Task name\n- ActionPlanTemplateId (Lookup): The parent template\n- Description (LongTextArea): Task description and instructions\n- DaysFromStart (Number): Number of days from plan start until this task is due\n- Priority (Picklist): Task priority: Low, Normal, High\n- DependsOnItemId (Lookup): Another template item that must be completed first\n### ActionPlanItem (6 fields)\n- Name (Text): Task name from the template item\n- ActionPlanId (Lookup): The parent action plan\n- AssignedToId (Lookup): The user assigned to complete this task\n- DueDate (Date): Calculated due date based on plan start and offset\n- Status (Picklist): Task status: Not Started, In Progress, Completed\n- Priority (Picklist): Task priority: Low, Normal, High\n### StageDefinition (5 fields)\n- Name (Text): Stage name\n- ObjectType (Picklist): The object this stage applies to: Initiative, Position, Assignment\n- StageOrder (Number): Sequential order of this stage in the progression\n- Description (LongTextArea): Description of what this stage represents\n- ActionPlanTemplateId (Lookup): Template to trigger when a record enters this stage\n\n## Object Relationships\n- Account -> Contact (parent): Person Accounts have an associated Contact record that stores individual-specific fields\n- Account -> ContactProfile (parent): Accounts can have a Contact Profile with extended fundraising attributes\n- Account -> AccountContactRelationship (parent): Accounts are linked to contacts through Account Contact Relationships for household and organizational membership\n- Account -> ContactPointAddress (parent): Accounts have one or more contact point addresses\n- Contact -> Account (child): Each Contact belongs to an Account; for Person Accounts this is a one-to-one relationship\n- Contact -> ContactContactRelationship (parent): Contacts participate in interpersonal relationships\n- Contact -> OpportunityContactRole (parent): Contacts are linked to fundraising opportunities through contact roles\n- ContactProfile -> Account (child): Each Contact Profile belongs to a single constituent account\n- ContactProfile -> GiftCommitment (lookup): Contact profiles inform recurring commitment tracking and donor classification\n- PartyRelationshipGroup -> Account (child): Each group is represented by a Business Account\n- PartyRelationshipGroup -> AccountContactRelationship (parent): Group membership is tracked through Account Contact Relationship records\n- AccountContactRelationship -> Account (child): Each ACR links to the organization or group account\n- AccountContactRelationship -> Contact (child): Each ACR links to the individual contact\n- AccountContactRelationship -> PartyRelationshipGroup (lookup): ACRs connect individuals to Party Relationship Group households\n- ContactContactRelationship -> Contact (child): Links to the first individual in the relationship\n- ContactContactRelationship -> PartyRoleRelationship (child): References the party role that defines the relationship type and reciprocal labels\n- AccountAccountRelationship -> Account (child): Links to the first organization account\n- AccountAccountRelationship -> PartyRoleRelationship (child): References the party role defining the relationship type\n- PartyRoleRelationship -> ContactContactRelationship (parent): Party roles are used by Contact Contact Relationships\n- PartyRoleRelationship -> AccountAccountRelationship (parent): Party roles are used by Account Account Relationships\n- ContactPointAddress -> Account (child): Each address belongs to a constituent account\n- ContactPointAddress -> PartyRelationshipGroup (lookup): Household members may share addresses through the group\n- ContactPointEmail -> Account (child): Each email belongs to a constituent account\n- ContactPointPhone -> Account (child): Each phone number belongs to a constituent account\n- Opportunity -> Account (child): Each opportunity is associated with a donor account\n- Opportunity -> Campaign (child): Opportunities are sourced from campaigns\n- Opportunity -> OpportunityContactRole (parent): Opportunities have contact roles identifying involved individuals\n- Opportunity -> GiftCommitment (lookup): Won opportunities can become gift commitments\n- OpportunityContactRole -> Opportunity (child): Each contact role belongs to an opportunity\n- OpportunityContactRole -> Contact (child): Each contact role references an individual\n- OpportunityContactRole -> GiftSoftCredit (lookup): Contact roles can inform soft credit attribution\n- GiftCommitment -> Account (child): Each commitment belongs to a donor account\n- GiftCommitment -> GiftCommitmentSchedule (parent): Commitments have one or more schedules defining installment patterns\n- GiftCommitment -> GiftTransaction (parent): Commitments generate gift transactions for each installment\n- GiftCommitment -> Opportunity (child): Commitments can originate from fundraising opportunities\n- GiftCommitmentSchedule -> GiftCommitment (child): Each schedule belongs to a gift commitment\n- GiftCommitmentSchedule -> PaymentInstrument (lookup): Schedules reference the payment method used for installments\n- GiftCommitmentChangeAttributionLog -> GiftCommitment (child): Each log entry references the modified commitment\n- GiftCommitmentChangeAttributionLog -> Campaign (child): Changes are attributed to campaigns for ROI analysis\n- GiftTransaction -> Account (child): Each transaction belongs to a donor account\n- GiftTransaction -> GiftCommitment (child): Transactions fulfill commitment installments\n- GiftTransaction -> Campaign (child): Transactions are attributed to campaigns\n- GiftTransaction -> GiftTransactionDesignation (parent): Transactions are allocated to designations through junction records\n- GiftTransaction -> GiftSoftCredit (parent): Transactions can have soft credit recipients\n- PaymentInstrument -> Account (child): Each payment instrument belongs to a donor account\n- PaymentInstrument -> GiftCommitmentSchedule (lookup): Payment instruments are linked to commitment schedules for recurring processing\n- GiftEntry -> Account (child): Each gift entry references a donor account\n- GiftEntry -> GiftBatch (child): Entries are grouped in batches for bulk processing\n- GiftEntry -> GiftTransaction (lookup): Processing creates a gift transaction from each entry\n- GiftBatch -> GiftEntry (parent): Batches contain multiple gift entries\n- GiftBatch -> GiftBatchTemplate (child): Each batch uses a template for field configuration\n- GiftBatchTemplate -> GiftBatch (parent): Templates are applied to gift batches\n- GiftDesignation -> GiftTransactionDesignation (parent): Designations receive allocations through gift transaction designation junction records\n- GiftDesignation -> GiftDefaultDesignation (parent): Designations can be set as defaults at various levels\n- GiftTransactionDesignation -> GiftTransaction (child): Each allocation belongs to a gift transaction\n- GiftTransactionDesignation -> GiftDesignation (child): Each allocation references a gift designation fund\n- GiftDefaultDesignation -> GiftDesignation (child): Each default references a gift designation\n- GiftDefaultDesignation -> Campaign (lookup): Default designations can be set at the campaign level\n- GiftDefaultDesignation -> GiftCommitment (lookup): Default designations can be set at the commitment level\n- GiftSoftCredit -> GiftTransaction (child): Each soft credit references a gift transaction\n- GiftSoftCredit -> Account (child): Each soft credit is attributed to a constituent account\n- GiftSoftCredit -> ContactContactRelationship (lookup): Relationships between constituents inform soft credit decisions\n- Campaign -> OutreachSourceCode (parent): Campaigns contain outreach source codes for granular attribution\n- Campaign -> GiftTransaction (parent): Gift transactions are attributed to campaigns\n- Campaign -> GiftCommitment (parent): Gift commitments are linked to campaigns\n- Campaign -> Opportunity (parent): Fundraising opportunities are sourced from campaigns\n- OutreachSourceCode -> Campaign (child): Each source code belongs to a campaign\n- OutreachSourceCode -> GiftTransaction (parent): Transactions reference source codes for granular attribution\n- OutreachSourceCode -> GiftCommitmentChangeAttributionLog (parent): Commitment changes reference source codes for ROI tracking\n- Program -> Benefit (parent): Programs offer specific benefits and services to participants\n- Program -> ProgramEnrollment (parent): Participants enroll in programs\n- Program -> ProgramCohort (parent): Programs organize participants into cohorts\n- Program -> OutcomeDefinition (lookup): Programs are measured against defined outcomes\n- Benefit -> Program (child): Each benefit belongs to a program\n- Benefit -> BenefitType (child): Benefits are classified by type\n- Benefit -> BenefitDisbursement (parent): Benefits are delivered through disbursement records\n- Benefit -> BenefitSchedule (parent): Benefits have delivery schedules\n- BenefitType -> Benefit (parent): Benefit types classify one or more benefits across programs\n- UnitOfMeasure -> Benefit (parent): Units of measure are assigned to benefits for quantity tracking\n- ProgramEnrollment -> Account (child): Each enrollment references a participant account\n- ProgramEnrollment -> Program (child): Each enrollment references a program\n- ProgramEnrollment -> ProgramCohort (lookup): Enrollees can be assigned to cohorts within the program\n- ProgramCohort -> Program (child): Each cohort belongs to a program\n- ProgramCohort -> ProgramCohortMember (parent): Cohorts contain member records linking to participants\n- ProgramCohortMember -> ProgramCohort (child): Each member record belongs to a cohort\n- ProgramCohortMember -> Account (child): Each member references a participant account\n- BenefitDisbursement -> Benefit (child): Each disbursement delivers a specific benefit\n- BenefitDisbursement -> Account (child): Each disbursement goes to a participant account\n- BenefitDisbursement -> BenefitSession (lookup): Disbursements may be linked to scheduled benefit sessions\n- BenefitSchedule -> Benefit (child): Each schedule defines delivery timing for a benefit\n- BenefitSchedule -> BenefitSession (parent): Schedules generate individual benefit sessions\n- BenefitSession -> BenefitSchedule (child): Each session is generated from a benefit schedule\n- BenefitSession -> BenefitDisbursement (parent): Session attendance creates disbursement records\n- BenefitAssignment -> Account (child): Each assignment references a participant account\n- BenefitAssignment -> Benefit (child): Each assignment references a specific benefit\n- GoalDefinition -> OutcomeDefinition (lookup): Goals connect to outcome definitions for measurement\n- GoalDefinition -> CarePlan (lookup): Care plans reference goal definitions for participant-level tracking\n- GoalDefinition -> Program (lookup): Goals are associated with programs they measure\n- Case -> Account (child): Each case references a participant account\n- Case -> CarePlan (parent): Cases can have personalized care plans\n- Case -> CaseReferral (parent): Cases can be created from referrals\n- Case -> InteractionSummary (parent): Cases have interaction summaries documenting meetings and notes\n- CarePlan -> Account (child): Each care plan serves a participant account\n- CarePlan -> Case (child): Care plans are linked to cases\n- CarePlan -> CarePlanTemplate (child): Care plans are built from templates\n- CarePlan -> GoalDefinition (lookup): Care plans reference goal definitions for tracking progress\n- CarePlanTemplate -> CarePlan (parent): Templates are used to create care plan instances\n- CarePlanTemplate -> CarePlanTemplateBenefit (parent): Templates include pre-configured benefit assignments\n- CarePlanTemplate -> CarePlanTemplateGoal (parent): Templates include pre-configured goal definitions\n- CarePlanTemplateBenefit -> CarePlanTemplate (child): Each template benefit belongs to a care plan template\n- CarePlanTemplateBenefit -> Benefit (child): References the benefit to be included\n- CarePlanTemplateGoal -> CarePlanTemplate (child): Each template goal belongs to a care plan template\n- CarePlanTemplateGoal -> GoalDefinition (child): References the goal definition to track\n- CaseReferral -> Case (child): Each referral is linked to a case\n- CaseReferral -> Account (lookup): Referrals reference the participant account\n- AssessmentTask -> Account (child): Each assessment is completed for a participant\n- AssessmentTask -> DiscoveryFramework (child): Assessments use a configured discovery framework\n- AssessmentTask -> Case (lookup): Assessments are linked to participant cases\n- DiscoveryFramework -> AssessmentTask (parent): Frameworks are used to create assessment task instances\n- InteractionSummary -> Account (child): Each interaction is linked to a constituent account\n- InteractionSummary -> Case (lookup): Interactions can be linked to a case for case management context\n- OutcomeDefinition -> Program (lookup): Outcomes link to the programs that drive them\n- OutcomeDefinition -> Indicator (parent): Outcomes are measured through indicators\n- OutcomeDefinition -> GoalDefinition (lookup): Outcomes connect to program goals\n- Indicator -> OutcomeDefinition (child): Each indicator measures a specific outcome\n- Indicator -> IndicatorResult (parent): Indicators accumulate result data points over time\n- IndicatorResult -> Indicator (child): Each result belongs to an indicator\n- IndicatorResult -> Program (lookup): Results are collected from program activities\n- VolunteerInitiative -> JobPosition (parent): Initiatives are staffed by job positions\n- VolunteerInitiative -> Program (lookup): Volunteer initiatives support program delivery\n- Position -> JobPosition (parent): Generic positions are customized as job positions for specific initiatives\n- Position -> Competency (lookup): Positions may require specific competencies\n- JobPosition -> VolunteerInitiative (child): Each job position belongs to a volunteer initiative\n- JobPosition -> Position (child): Each job position references a generic position\n- JobPosition -> JobPositionShift (parent): Job positions have one or more shifts\n- JobPositionShift -> JobPosition (child): Each shift belongs to a job position\n- JobPositionShift -> JobPositionAssignment (parent): Shifts have volunteer assignments\n- JobPositionAssignment -> JobPositionShift (child): Each assignment belongs to a shift\n- JobPositionAssignment -> Account (child): Each assignment references a volunteer account\n- Competency -> PersonCompetency (parent): Competencies are held by individuals through person competency records\n- Competency -> Position (lookup): Positions may require specific competencies\n- PersonCompetency -> Account (child): Each person competency belongs to a volunteer account\n- PersonCompetency -> Competency (child): References the competency definition\n- Examination -> PersonExamination (parent): Examinations are taken by individuals through person examination records\n- PersonExamination -> Account (child): Each exam result belongs to a volunteer account\n- PersonExamination -> Examination (child): References the examination definition\n- PersonLocationAvailability -> Account (child): Each location availability belongs to a volunteer account\n- FundingOpportunity -> GrantApplication (parent): Funding opportunities receive grant applications\n- FundingOpportunity -> Program (lookup): Funding opportunities may be tied to specific programs\n- GrantApplication -> FundingOpportunity (child): Each application is for a specific funding opportunity\n- GrantApplication -> Account (child): Applications reference the applicant organization account\n- GrantApplication -> ApplicationReview (parent): Applications are evaluated through review records\n- GrantApplication -> FundingAward (parent): Approved applications receive funding awards\n- ApplicationReview -> GrantApplication (child): Each review evaluates a specific application\n- Budget -> GrantApplication (child): Each budget belongs to a grant application\n- Budget -> FundingAward (lookup): Approved budgets inform funding award amounts\n- FundingAward -> GrantApplication (child): Each award results from an approved application\n- FundingAward -> Account (child): Awards are linked to the grantee organization\n- FundingAward -> OutcomeDefinition (lookup): Awards require grantees to report on defined outcomes\n- ActionPlan -> ActionPlanTemplate (child): Each plan is created from a template\n- ActionPlan -> ActionPlanItem (parent): Plans contain task items to be completed\n- ActionPlanTemplate -> ActionPlan (parent): Templates are used to create action plan instances\n- ActionPlanTemplate -> ActionPlanTemplateItem (parent): Templates contain template item definitions\n- ActionPlanTemplateItem -> ActionPlanTemplate (child): Each item belongs to a template\n- ActionPlanItem -> ActionPlan (child): Each item belongs to an action plan\n- StageDefinition -> ActionPlanTemplate (lookup): Stage transitions can trigger action plan templates\n- StageDefinition -> VolunteerInitiative (lookup): Stages track volunteer initiative lifecycle progress\n\n## Cross-Domain Connections\n- Constituents <-> Households & Groups: Individuals belong to households\n- Constituents <-> Relationships: Constituents have relationships\n- Constituents <-> Contact Information: Accounts have contact information\n- Constituents <-> Fundraising Pipeline: Donors are constituents\n- Constituents <-> Gift Transactions: Gift transactions belong to donors\n- Constituents <-> Gift Entry & Processing: Donors matched during gift entry\n- Constituents <-> Soft Credits: Soft credits attributed to constituents\n- Constituents <-> Program Management: Program participants are constituents\n- Constituents <-> Case Management: Case subjects are constituents\n- Constituents <-> Volunteer Management: Volunteers are constituents\n- Constituents <-> Grantmaking: Grant applicants are constituents\n- Constituents <-> Security & Access: Constituent data access is secured\n- Constituents <-> Setup & Configuration: Account model configured in setup\n- Households & Groups <-> Relationships: Household members have inter-relationships\n- Households & Groups <-> Contact Information: Households share contact information\n- Households & Groups <-> Campaigns & Outreach: Household addressing for campaign mailings\n- Relationships <-> Soft Credits: Relationships inform soft credit decisions\n- Relationships <-> Grantmaking: Organization relationships inform grants\n- Relationships <-> Setup & Configuration: Relationship types configured in setup\n- Contact Information <-> Campaigns & Outreach: Contact points used for campaign outreach\n- Fundraising Pipeline <-> Gift Commitments: Opportunities become commitments\n- Fundraising Pipeline <-> Gift Transactions: Opportunities produce transactions\n- Fundraising Pipeline <-> Campaigns & Outreach: Campaigns source fundraising\n- Fundraising Pipeline <-> Gift Designations: Opportunities have default designations\n- Fundraising Pipeline <-> Soft Credits: Opportunity contact roles drive soft credits\n- Fundraising Pipeline <-> Agentforce & Einstein AI: AI generates gift proposals\n- Fundraising Pipeline <-> Action Plans: Action plans drive cultivation steps\n- Fundraising Pipeline <-> Setup & Configuration: Fundraising settings in setup\n- Fundraising Pipeline <-> Grantmaking: Grants use the fundraising pipeline\n- Gift Commitments <-> Gift Transactions: Commitments generate transactions\n- Gift Commitments <-> Gift Entry & Processing: Gift entry creates commitments\n- Gift Commitments <-> Gift Designations: Commitments allocated to designations\n- Gift Commitments <-> Campaigns & Outreach: Commitments attributed to campaigns\n- Gift Transactions <-> Gift Entry & Processing: Gift entry creates transactions\n- Gift Transactions <-> Gift Designations: Transactions linked to designations\n- Gift Transactions <-> Soft Credits: Transactions have soft credits\n- Gift Transactions <-> Campaigns & Outreach: Transactions attributed to campaigns\n- Gift Entry & Processing <-> Gift Designations: Designations applied during entry\n- Gift Entry & Processing <-> Campaigns & Outreach: Campaign and source code set during entry\n- Gift Entry & Processing <-> Agentforce & Einstein AI: AI assists gift data entry\n- Gift Designations <-> Campaigns & Outreach: Campaigns have default designations\n- Gift Designations <-> Outcome Management: Designation data feeds impact reporting\n- Gift Designations <-> Setup & Configuration: DPE calculates designation rollups\n- Campaigns & Outreach <-> Action Plans: Campaigns trigger action plans\n- Campaigns & Outreach <-> Agentforce & Einstein AI: AI provides campaign insights\n- Campaigns & Outreach <-> Setup & Configuration: DPE aggregates campaign metrics\n- Program Management <-> Outcome Management: Programs measured by outcomes\n- Program Management <-> Case Management: Programs serve case participants\n- Program Management <-> Grantmaking: Grants fund programs\n- Program Management <-> Volunteer Management: Volunteers support programs\n- Program Management <-> Action Plans: Action plans automate program steps\n- Program Management <-> Setup & Configuration: Program settings in setup\n- Program Management <-> Agentforce & Einstein AI: AI summarizes program benefits\n- Case Management <-> Outcome Management: Case outcomes tracked\n- Case Management <-> Agentforce & Einstein AI: AI summarizes notes\n- Case Management <-> Action Plans: Action plans automate case steps\n- Case Management <-> Security & Access: Case data requires access controls\n- Case Management <-> Setup & Configuration: Case settings in setup\n- Outcome Management <-> Grantmaking: Outcomes support grant reporting\n- Volunteer Management <-> Action Plans: Action plans automate volunteer onboarding\n- Volunteer Management <-> Agentforce & Einstein AI: AI assists volunteer matching\n- Volunteer Management <-> Setup & Configuration: Volunteer settings in setup\n- Grantmaking <-> Agentforce & Einstein AI: AI summarizes grant applications\n- Grantmaking <-> Action Plans: Action plans support grant review workflows\n- Security & Access <-> Setup & Configuration: Permissions configured in setup\n\n## Data Flows\n### Constituents\n1. Admin enables Person Accounts and configures account record types\n2. Individual constituents are created as Person Accounts with Contact Profile\n3. Organizations are created as Business Accounts with optional hierarchy\n4. Constituent records accumulate activities, gifts, and program participation over time\n5. Fundraising and program staff access a unified 360-degree constituent view\n### Households & Groups\n1. Admin creates a Party Relationship Group with Type Household\n2. Individual Person Accounts are linked as members via Account Contact Relationships\n3. Each member receives a role such as Head of Household, Spouse, or Dependent\n4. Membership dates track household composition changes over time\n5. Household-level reporting aggregates donations and activities across all members\n### Relationships\n1. Admin configures available relationship types via Party Role Relationships\n2. Staff creates relationship records between constituents as connections are discovered\n3. Each relationship specifies roles for both parties and an active status\n4. Relationship data surfaces on constituent records for a 360-degree view\n5. Fundraisers and program staff use relationship networks to inform strategy\n### Contact Information\n1. Admin configures contact point fields and page layouts\n2. Staff creates contact point records when gathering constituent information\n3. Each contact point is linked to the constituent's account record\n4. Primary designation is set for the preferred contact method per type\n5. Contact points drive campaign targeting and communication workflows\n### Fundraising Pipeline\n1. Fundraiser identifies a prospective donor or grant opportunity\n2. Opportunity record is created with expected amount and close date\n3. Development officer cultivates the relationship through meetings and proposals\n4. Opportunity moves through pipeline stages toward close\n5. Won opportunity converts to a gift commitment or direct gift transaction\n### Gift Commitments\n1. Donor agrees to a pledge or recurring gift commitment\n2. Gift Commitment record is created with initial schedule\n3. Automated processing creates gift transactions per the schedule\n4. Donor requests changes which are tracked in the Change Attribution Log\n5. Commitment status updates automatically based on payment patterns\n### Gift Transactions\n1. Gift is received via one-time payment, commitment installment, or batch entry\n2. Gift Transaction record is created with amount, payment method, and donor\n3. Transaction status progresses from Unpaid through Paid or Failed\n4. Designation allocations and soft credits are applied to the transaction\n5. Acknowledgment is tracked and sent to the donor\n### Gift Entry & Processing\n1. Staff selects entry method: single gift window, grid, or CSV import\n2. Donor information is entered or looked up from existing accounts\n3. Gift details are captured: amount, payment method, commitment, designations\n4. For batches, entries are validated with dry run before processing\n5. Processing creates gift transactions and updates related records\n### Gift Designations\n1. Admin creates gift designations for each fund and purpose\n2. One designation is set as the org-wide default for unrestricted gifts\n3. Default designations are configured at campaign and commitment levels\n4. During gift processing, amounts are allocated to designations via hierarchy\n5. Rollup totals on designation records provide real-time fund balance visibility\n### Soft Credits\n1. Gift is received and primary donor receives hard credit on the transaction\n2. Staff identifies influencers, household members, or tribute honorees\n3. Gift Soft Credit records are created linking credited constituents to the transaction\n4. Matching gift transactions are linked to original donations via lookup\n5. Soft credit totals roll up to constituent records for stewardship reporting\n### Campaigns & Outreach\n1. Admin creates campaign with budget, dates, and target audience\n2. Outreach Source Codes are created for each channel, message, and audience combination\n3. Communications go out with source code tracking identifiers\n4. Donor responses are captured as gift entries with campaign and source code attribution\n5. Performance metrics aggregate across campaigns for ROI reporting\n### Program Management\n1. Admin creates program with benefits, schedules, and goal definitions\n2. Participants enroll in the program and are assigned to cohorts\n3. Benefit sessions are scheduled and volunteers or staff deliver services\n4. Disbursements are recorded tracking attendance and service delivery\n5. Program data feeds outcome measurement and impact reporting\n### Case Management\n1. Referral is received and processed through intake flow\n2. Case record is created and assessment is administered\n3. Case manager creates a personalized care plan from a template\n4. Participant receives services and progress is tracked via interaction summaries\n5. Care plan goals are evaluated and adjusted based on assessment results\n### Outcome Management\n1. Admin defines outcome strategy with outcome definitions and indicators\n2. Programs and benefits are linked to the outcomes they drive\n3. Staff collects indicator data through assessments and program tracking\n4. Indicator results are analyzed to evaluate program effectiveness\n5. Impact reports are generated for donors, boards, and funders\n### Volunteer Management\n1. Admin creates volunteer initiative with positions and job positions\n2. Qualifications are defined and shifts are scheduled for each job position\n3. Volunteer matching identifies candidates based on competencies and availability\n4. Volunteers sign up through the portal or are assigned by staff\n5. Hours are tracked through shift assignment status and reported on\n### Grantmaking\n1. Admin creates funding opportunities with eligibility criteria and deadlines\n2. Applicants discover opportunities and submit applications through the portal\n3. Internal reviewers evaluate applications and score proposals\n4. Approved applications receive budget approval and funding awards\n5. Grantees report on outcomes and impact of funded activities\n### Agentforce & Einstein AI\n1. Admin enables Einstein Generative AI and assigns Copilot permission sets\n2. Einstein Summary components are added to program, account, and grantmaking page layouts\n3. Major gift officers request AI-generated gift proposals through Copilot\n4. Staff uses Einstein summaries to quickly review programs, notes, and applications\n5. Agentforce agents automate routine tasks and assist portal users\n### Action Plans\n1. Admin creates action plan templates for common processes\n2. Staff applies a template to a record (opportunity, case, initiative)\n3. System generates tasks with calculated due dates and assignments\n4. Tasks are completed in sequence following dependency rules\n5. Stage transitions trigger additional action plans as needed\n### Security & Access\n1. Admin assigns Nonprofit Cloud permission set licenses to users\n2. Permission set groups are configured for each functional role\n3. Field-level security and sharing rules protect sensitive data\n4. Muting permission sets remove unnecessary access for specific roles\n5. Users receive exactly the permissions needed for their job function\n### Setup & Configuration\n1. Admin enables desired Nonprofit Cloud features in Setup\n2. Fundraising settings are configured for commitment processing behavior\n3. Picklist values and record types are customized for the organization\n4. Data Processing Engine is configured for rollup calculations\n5. Permission sets and security settings are assigned to users\n\n## Links\nUse these URLs when mentioning domains or components:\n- [Constituents](https://epugach.github.io/product-explorer/nonprofitcloud/#/constituents)\n- [Households & Groups](https://epugach.github.io/product-explorer/nonprofitcloud/#/households)\n- [Relationships](https://epugach.github.io/product-explorer/nonprofitcloud/#/relationships)\n- [Contact Information](https://epugach.github.io/product-explorer/nonprofitcloud/#/contact_points)\n- [Fundraising Pipeline](https://epugach.github.io/product-explorer/nonprofitcloud/#/fundraising)\n- [Gift Commitments](https://epugach.github.io/product-explorer/nonprofitcloud/#/gift_commitments)\n- [Gift Transactions](https://epugach.github.io/product-explorer/nonprofitcloud/#/gift_transactions)\n- [Gift Entry & Processing](https://epugach.github.io/product-explorer/nonprofitcloud/#/gift_entry)\n- [Gift Designations](https://epugach.github.io/product-explorer/nonprofitcloud/#/designations)\n- [Soft Credits](https://epugach.github.io/product-explorer/nonprofitcloud/#/soft_credits)\n- [Campaigns & Outreach](https://epugach.github.io/product-explorer/nonprofitcloud/#/campaigns)\n- [Program Management](https://epugach.github.io/product-explorer/nonprofitcloud/#/programs)\n- [Case Management](https://epugach.github.io/product-explorer/nonprofitcloud/#/case_management)\n- [Outcome Management](https://epugach.github.io/product-explorer/nonprofitcloud/#/outcomes)\n- [Volunteer Management](https://epugach.github.io/product-explorer/nonprofitcloud/#/volunteers)\n- [Grantmaking](https://epugach.github.io/product-explorer/nonprofitcloud/#/grantmaking)\n- [Agentforce & Einstein AI](https://epugach.github.io/product-explorer/nonprofitcloud/#/agentforce)\n- [Action Plans](https://epugach.github.io/product-explorer/nonprofitcloud/#/action_plans)\n- [Security & Access](https://epugach.github.io/product-explorer/nonprofitcloud/#/security)\n- [Setup & Configuration](https://epugach.github.io/product-explorer/nonprofitcloud/#/setup)\n";
